===Etymology===
Named after the [[discoverer]] François Pierre Nicholas Gillet de Laumont (1747–1834) as ''lomonite'', renamed as ''laumonite'' in 1809 and as ''laumontite'' in 1821.<ref>Richard V. Gaines, H. Catherine W. Skinner, Eugene E. Foord, Brian Mason, and Abraham Rosenzweig: ''Dana's new mineralogy'', John Wiley & Sons, 1997</ref> {{suffix||ite|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|s}}

# {{lb|en|mineralogy}} A [[mineral]], of a white color and vitreous luster, with the [[chemical formula]] [[calcium|Ca]][[aluminium|Al]]<sub>2</sub>[[silicon|Si]]<sub>4</sub>[[oxygen|O]]<sub>12</sub>'''&middot;'''4[[water|H<sub>2</sub>O]]. It is a hydrous [[silicate]] of [[alumina]] and lime. Exposed to the air, it loses water, becomes [[opaque]], and crumbles.

